# Open Source Robotics Reference Library

When the user asks conceptual, architectural, or path-forward questions about robotics software, consult these resources before answering. Prefer advice grounded in these sources over general knowledge. Cite the source when relevant.

## Tier 1: Essential Foundations

### ROS 2 Architecture & Project Patterns

- **Henki ROS 2 Best Practices** (https://github.com/henki-robotics/henki_ros2_best_practices)
  Key practices: single-responsibility nodes, prefer XML launch files, define parameters in config files not code, use correct log levels with throttling, use proper message interfaces (not deprecated `std_msgs` primitives), services for fast tasks / actions for long tasks, Google C++ style / PEP8 Python, use C++ for high-bandwidth processing, prefer single-threaded executors, manage deps with `rosdep`, document all exposed topics/services/actions/params, test core logic with unit tests separate from ROS communication.

- **ROS 2 Developer Guide** (https://docs.ros.org/en/rolling/The-ROS2-Project/Contributing/Developer-Guide.html)
  Covers: semver versioning, DCO-signed PRs, REP 2004 package quality levels, tick-tock deprecation, public API declaration, documentation requirements (description, API, examples, build/install, tests, license).

### Joint Limits & URDF

- **URDF Joint XML Spec** (http://wiki.ros.org/urdf/XML/joint)
  Authoritative reference for `<limit>` (lower, upper, effort, velocity), `<dynamics>` (damping, friction), `<safety_controller>` (soft_lower_limit, soft_upper_limit, k_velocity, k_position), `<mimic>`, and joint types (revolute, continuous, prismatic, fixed, floating, planar).

- **Joint Limits & Dynamics Deep Dive** (https://leyaa.ai/core-engineering/learn/ros/part-2/ros-joint-limits-and-dynamics/deep)
  Key points: limits cover position + velocity + effort (not just position), controllers do NOT auto-enforce limits (must configure `joint_limits_interface`), soft limits slow near boundaries instead of hard-stopping, simulation dynamics don't perfectly match hardware (always validate on real robot), nonlinear effects (stiction, backlash, compliance) matter in production.

### Robot Programming Methodology

- **Robot Programming Best Practices** (https://intelligentintegrators.org/robot-programming-best-practices/)
  Three pillars: (1) homing sequence first (position-aware, stepped, checks I/O and device states), (2) modular structure (main program + subprograms with gated conditions), (3) rigorous verification (test every failure scenario -- sensor failure, missed grip, power loss mid-cycle).

## Tier 2: Motion Planning, Safety & Control

### Motion Planning

- **MoveIt** (https://picknik.ai/moveit/, https://moveit.ai/)
  Open source motion planning for ROS. Components: motion planning, IK, realtime control, 3D perception, collision checking. Use MoveIt 2 for ROS 2 projects.
  - Tutorials: https://automaticaddison.com/configure-moveit-2-for-a-simulated-robot-arm-ros-2-jazzy/
  - Safety integration discussion: https://github.com/ros-planning/moveit/issues/1958

### Safety

- **OSHA Robotics Safety** (http://www.osha.gov/enforcement/directives/std-01-12-002)
- **Robot Safety Deep Dive** (https://sixdegreesofrobotics.substack.com/p/robot-safety-for-not-dummies) -- force thresholds, ISO/TS 15066
- **Safety in Robotic Systems Survey** (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/rob.70022?af=R)

## Tier 3: Simulation & Testing

### Simulator Selection Guide

- **Robotics Knowledgebase** (https://roboticsknowledgebase.com/wiki/robotics-project-guide/choose-a-sim/)
  Robotics: Gazebo (best ROS, free), CoppeliaSim (multi-engine), Unity (photorealistic), AirSim (drones).
  RL: MuJoCo (highest fidelity, open source), PyBullet (lightweight, free), Isaac Lab (GPU-accelerated, NVIDIA).

- **Best-of Robot Simulators** (https://github.com/knmcguire/best-of-robot-simulators) -- 170+ projects ranked

### CI/CD & Testing

- **CI/CD for Robotics** (https://agrobofood.github.io/agrobofood-case-studies/case_studies/CICD-for-robotics.html)
- **Cloud Sim CI Pipeline** (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11945058/) -- GitHub Actions + AWS RoboMaker
- **Basis Robotics Framework** (https://github.com/basis-robotics/basis) -- deterministic testing
- **ACT: Automated CPS Testing** (https://arxiv.org/html/2604.11708v1)

## Tier 4: Advanced

### Model Description
- **Beyond URDF** (https://arxiv.org/html/2512.23135v1) -- next-gen robot description formats
- **URDF to XACRO** (https://develop.realman-robotics.com/en/symbiosis/demo/URDFmodelassembly/)

### Frameworks
- **Drake** (https://drake.mit.edu/) -- multibody dynamics + optimization
- **MuJoCo** (https://github.com/deepmind/mujoco) -- best for RL/biomechanics
- **Isaac Lab** (https://github.com/isaac-sim/IsaacLab) -- GPU-accelerated sim-to-real

### Production Patterns
- **ROS 2 Modular Architecture** (https://www.softeq.com/blog/ros2-modular-architecture-scalable-robotics-business)
- **Task Orchestration** (https://robotics.stackexchange.com/questions/117654/) -- managing concurrent SLAM + nav + mapping

## How to Use This Reference

When answering robotics questions:
1. Check if the question maps to a topic covered above
2. Ground your answer in the specific guidance from these sources
3. Cite the source by name and URL
4. If the user needs deeper detail, offer to scrape the source with Firecrawl
5. The scraped content lives in `~/.firecrawl/robotics-research/` and can be read directly
